Chapter 7: The Downlink
The purple pillar didn't just light up the sky; it hummed with a frequency that made the fillings in Jax’s teeth ache. As the four of them sprinted toward the center of the site, the fog began to take on a geometric quality, forming sharp, jagged cubes that floated in mid-air.
"Faster!" Kaelen urged, his boots kicking up sparks of Essence. He was pushing the group’s pace, his eyes locked on the light. "The Association wouldn't trigger a signal that large unless the evacuation was mandatory!"
"Kaelen, stop!" Ren shouted, skidding to a halt.
They were standing at the edge of a massive construction crater. In the center sat a metal platform—the "Extraction Pad"—but it wasn't empty.
Professor Aris was there. She was standing at a console, her back to them. Her movements were fluid, unlike the flickering Graves-type. But as she turned around, the light from the pillar reflected off her glasses, and Ren’s breath hitched.
[Target: Professor Aris]
[Status: SYNCED]
[Role: The Architect’s Hand]
"You made it," Aris said. Her voice was calm, maternal, and completely terrifying. "And with the 'Zero' still intact. Excellent."
"Professor!" Mira cried out, stepping forward. "What’s happening? The Voids... they’re everywhere! We need to leave!"
"Leave?" Aris tilted her head. "Mira, dear. You’ve spent three years studying the 'Veil'. Did you never wonder why it looks so much like a firewall?"
Kaelen stepped in front of Mira, his palms glowing with intense heat. "Back away from the console, Professor. Now. This isn't a training exercise. You’ve bypassed the Association’s safety protocols."
"The Association," Aris laughed, a soft, genuine sound. "They are the janitors of a house they don't own, Kaelen. They think they're 'Hunters.' In reality, they're just antivirus software that’s grown too old to catch the latest virus."
Ren looked at the pillar. In his vision, the "Download" bar was at 94%.
"She’s not evacuating us," Ren said. He walked past Kaelen, his eyes fixed on the base of the pillar. "She’s uploading the student bios. Every Rank, every Skill, every bit of 'Essence' in this site is being indexed."
Aris looked at Ren, her eyes widening behind her spectacles. "You really can see it, can't you? No gear, no Rank... and yet you see the code. You were the only 'Empty Vessel' in the school, Ren. The only one the System couldn't corrupt because there was nothing to attach to."
"What is she talking about?" Jax whispered, clutching his bruised arm.
"The 'Level Up' system isn't a gift," Ren said, his voice cold. "It’s a tagging system. The higher your Rank, the more of your 'Essence' the Void can recognize and consume. We aren't being trained to be heroes. We're being ripened."
"Ren, that's crazy," Kaelen snapped, though his flames flickered.
"Is it?" Aris stepped away from the console, spreading her arms. "The download is almost complete. Once the 'Administrator' has the data, the Veil over Aethelgard will be deleted. The 'Dormant Gate' will finally open, and the world will be... updated."
[Download Progress: 98%]
"Stop it," Ren said.
"With what, Ren?" Aris smiled. "You have 2 Mana left. I can see your 'Status' too. You’re a bug in the system, but you’re a small one."
Ren didn't look at Aris. He looked at the console. He saw the 'Logic' strings—thousands of them, flowing from the students' IDs into the purple light.
[Skill Alert: 'Structural Deconstruction' — Range: 5 meters.]
[Requirement: Physical Contact with the Core.]
"Jax, Mira... I need a distraction," Ren muttered.
"Ren, you can't be serious," Mira whispered.
"If that bar hits 100%, we aren't going home," Ren said. He looked at Kaelen. "Prodigy. If you’re as good as you say you are, hit her with everything. Don't aim for the Professor. Aim for the light."
Kaelen looked at the pillar, then at Ren. For a split second, the hierarchy of the school vanished. "Three seconds," Kaelen said. "That’s all I can give you before the feedback kills me."
"Three seconds is enough," Ren replied.
Kaelen roared, his entire body erupting in a pillar of white-hot flame. He lunged at the purple beam, not as a Hunter, but as a living torch.
"Pointless!" Aris screamed, her face finally contorting into something monstrous as she raised a hand to block him.
While the "Administrator's Hand" was focused on the A-Rank's fire, Ren threw himself into the pit. He didn't go for Aris. He dove for the console, his hand outstretched, the silver mark on his palm screaming with heat.
[Warning: Integrity Failure Imminent.]
[Do you wish to 'Overload' the Source?]
Delete it all, Ren thought.
His hand slammed onto the metal.
The first major clash between the "System" and the "Zero" has begun.
